In 1802, Thomas Jefferson wrote a letter to the Danbury Baptist Association to answer them, asking why he would not declare national fasting and thanksgiving days, as Washington and Adams did before him. The letter contains the phrase ‚Äúwall of separation between church and state‚Äù, which led to the erroneous ‚Äúreduction‚Äù of the article on establishment (US Constitution, Bill of Rights, Amendment I, Article III), which we use today. ‚ÄúWhy do I have freedom of religion ...?‚Äù The answer lay in Congress documents, as they relate to our Constitution, as we know it today. The process of drafting the First Amendment clearly clarified the intentions of the Founders; before they approved the final wording, the First Amendment went through almost a dozen different iterations and extensive discussions. ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt want in America what we had in the UK: we don‚Äôt want one nation to rule the nation. We will not all be Catholics, Anglicans, or any other denomination. We really want the principles of God, but we don‚Äôt want one nation to rule the nation. ‚Äù This intention was well understood as evidence in court decisions after the First Amendment. In 1799, the court declared: ‚ÄúIn our form of government, the Christian religion is the established religion; and all sects and denominations of Christians are in the same position. ‚Äù It must be understood that our founding fathers sought to achieve "freedom of religion" because of the repressive authority of the Roman Catholic Church. Not only Britain, but also most of Europe fell under the amazing authority of Roman Catholicism. Our founding fathers began to recognize many denominations of Christianity. In addition, they intended to recognize each denomination in the same way, in contrast to giving power to control any single denomination. This is the misinterpretation of reckless ‚Äúshorthand‚Äù, known as the ‚Äúseparation of church and state‚Äù. A more accurate statement is most likely the ‚Äúseparation of the denominations of the Church and the state.‚Äù This interpretation is fully supported by Congress documents regarding the Statement: ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt want in America what we had in the UK: we don‚Äôt want the nation to manage one denomination.
